ost popular and enduring formats, with a history as old as the medium itself. Bernard Timberg here offers a comprehensive history of the first fifty years of television talk, replete with memorable moments from a wide range of classic talk shows, as well as many of today's most popular programs. Dividing the history into five eras, he shows how the evolution of the television talk show is connected to both broad patterns in American culture and the economic, regulatory, technological, and social history of the broadcasting industry. Robert Erler's "A Guide to Television Talk" complements the text with an extensive "who's who" listing of important people and programs in the history of television talk.  afunded by Erler  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aTelevision talk showszUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aErler, Robert J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewcomb, Horace, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewcomb, Horace.1 aTimberg, Bernard M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb2 aErlerefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292796331423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292796331/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK